# LLM TurboQuant Development Rules

## Project Overview
TurboQuant: Extreme quantization (1-2 bit) for LLM inference on NVIDIA RTX 3050 (4GB VRAM) + 24GB RAM.
Target: Intel i5-11400H (AVX-512), CUDA Compute 8.6.

## Code Style
- C++: C++20, Google Style Guide, clang-format enforced
- Assembly: Intel syntax (.intel_syntax noprefix), every instruction commented
- CUDA: Compute Capability 8.6, shared memory preferred over global
- Python: PEP 8, type hints mandatory, black formatter, 100 char line length

## Performance Requirements
- All hot paths profiled with `perf` or `nvprof` before merge
- SIMD intrinsics required for vector ops (AVX-512: `_mm512_*`)
- Assembly only for critical paths consuming >10% total runtime
- CUDA kernels must achieve >70% occupancy
- Memory bandwidth utilization >60% for data-bound kernels

## Architecture
- `core/` = C++/CUDA/Assembly (zero Python dependencies)
- `python/` = Python bindings via pybind11 (depends on core)
- `deployment/` = API servers, Web UI, Docker (depends on python)

## Testing
- Unit tests for all quantization functions (accuracy < 1% degradation vs FP16)
- Benchmark tests: minimum 1.5x speedup vs Q4_K_M baseline
- Integration tests with llama.cpp GGML backend
- Memory leak checks: Valgrind + CUDA memcheck clean

## Memory Safety
- No raw pointers in public C++ APIs (use std::unique_ptr, std::span)
- RAII for all GPU memory allocations
- Bounds checking in debug builds (#ifndef NDEBUG)

## Build System
- CMake 3.20+ with Ninja generator
- ccache enabled for faster rebuilds
- Separate build configs: Debug, Release, Profile
- MAKEFLAGS=-j12 (12 hardware threads)

## Git Workflow
- Feature branches: `feature/turboquant-polar`, `feature/cuda-int2`
- Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `perf:`, `test:`, `docs:`
- Benchmarks required in PR description for performance changes
